T1  - Migraine and delayed ischaemic neurological deficit after subarachnoid haemorrhage in women: a case-control study.
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-1331.2007.01980.x
A1  - Dreier, J P
A1  - Kremer, C
A1  - Lammers, G
A1  - Lohmann, F
A1  - Hansen, H C
A1  - Valdueza, J M
Y1  - 2007//
Y2  - 20071017//
N2  - The aim of the present case-control study was to investigate the role of migraine as a potential risk factor for a delayed ischaemic neurological deficit (DIND) after subarachnoid haemorrhage (SAH). A telephone interview was performed in patients or their relatives to determine the prevalence of migraine. Thirty-six women aged <60 years had SAH with Hunt & Hess grade I-III and DIND (group A). This group was compared with an age-matched group of 36 female SAH patients, Hunt & Hess grade I-III without DIND (group B). The two populations were also characterized regarding hypertension, smoking, diabetes mellitus and alcohol use. A significant difference was only found for the prevalence of migraine with 47% in group A and 25% in group B (P < 0.05; odds ratio: 2.68, confidence interval: 0.99-7.29). Migraineurs revealed similar prevalences of risk factors independently of the presence of DINDs. This retrospective study suggests that women with migraine have a higher risk to develop a DIND than women without migraine.
