T1  - Risk of hemorrhagic stroke in Asian American ethnic groups.
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.1159/000085310
A1  - Klatsky, Arthur L
A1  - Friedman, Gary D
A1  - Sidney, Stephen
A1  - Kipp, Harald
A1  - Kubo, Ai
A1  - Armstrong, Mary Anne
Y1  - 2005//
Y2  - 20050425//
N2  - The sparseness of prospective data about hemorrhagic stroke (HS) risk among Asian American ethnic groups led to the investigation of 128,934 persons with self-classified ethnicity at health examinations in 1978-1985. Subsequently, 431 persons were hospitalized for HS; 31% for subarachnoid hemorrhage (SAH) and 69% for intracerebral hemorrhage (ICH). Ethnic predictors of HS were studied by Cox proportional hazard models with 7 covariates. With whites as reference, the adjusted relative risk (95% CI) of all Asians for HS was 1.6 (1.1-2.3, p = 0.01), due substantially to increased risks of SAH in Japanese people and ICH in Filipinos. These data mandate emphasis upon preventive measures in these groups.
